Date: 19 Feb 93 15:22:32 GMT
kevinc@solman.kpc.com (Kevin Cameron) writes:

> I am a little confused by the key revokation post by John Perry.

[lots of stuff deleted]

> What I don't understand is why didn't Vesselin sign the outer message?
> It seems that a letter from Vesselin which is signed by John is not
> a secure way to revoke a key.  I`m not worried about the security of
> messages to/from John personally, but I do worry that we will all
> become accustomed to sloppy procedures such as this.  If so, someday
> someone will forge a message like this to cause someone else's key
> to be revoked.

The problem is that John messed something, IMHO. Here is what
happened.

I composed the message that John posted, singed with without
encryption, but WITH ASCII ARMOR, and sent it to John. I didn't use
clearsig, because my intention was that this message should be
distributed widely and I wanted to prevent some mailers from mungling
it. Since the message is not encrypted, everybody who has PGP can read
and verify my signature. But those who do NOT have PGP, cannot read
the message.

Obviously, John has run PGP on that message and has obtained the clean
text. Then he has posted it to the net in human-redable form,
clearsigning it. Unfortunately, this way he has also destroyed my
signature, effectively replacing it with his own.

Since the message that I signed was first signed by John, by removing
my signature and signing the result, John has obtained a message,
doubly signed by him, which explains your results.

There's nothing bad in what John has done, except that the message he
posted has NO authentication value. More exactly, it is equivalent of
a message from him, saying "My old key is no longer valid" and signing
it twice. The result does not carry my confirmation that it is indeed
so, and thus it is useless to post it to the world... :-)

Anyway, here is the message that I sent to John, in its original form.
It contains my signature. Hopefully, this will clear the
misunderstandings.

Regards,
Vesselin

